{
  "executive_summary": "Design a unified API gateway architecture for a logistics platform serving three distinct consumer types (mobile, B2B partners, internal services). The gateway centralizes authentication, rate limiting, and traffic isolation — eliminating the current inconsistency where each service independently implements these cross-cutting concerns. The architecture uses a single gateway deployment with three logical ingress paths, each enforcing consumer-specific policies before routing to backend services.",

  "architecture": {
    "components": [
      {
        "name": "API Gateway (Edge)",
        "responsibility": "Single entry point for all external traffic. Terminates TLS, enforces authentication, applies rate limiting, performs request routing, and emits access logs/metrics. Runs as a cluster of stateless instances behind a load balancer.",
        "boundaries": "Handles ONLY cross-cutting concerns (auth, rate limiting, routing, logging). Contains ZERO business logic. Never calls databases directly — delegates all domain operations to backend services."
      },
      {
        "name": "Mobile Ingress Pipeline",
        "responsibility": "Gateway route group for mobile app traffic. Enforces JWT/OAuth2 bearer token authentication, applies 100 req/min per-user rate limit, strips sensitive headers, and routes to backend services.",
        "boundaries": "Scoped to /api/v1/mobile/* path prefix (or equivalent host-based routing). Only accepts traffic from public internet on the mobile-designated endpoints."
      },
      {
        "name": "Partner Ingress Pipeline",
        "responsibility": "Gateway route group for B2B partner integrations. Validates API key authentication (via header), applies 1,000 req/min per-partner rate limit, manages webhook registration and delivery, and enforces partner-specific access scopes.",
        "boundaries": "Scoped to /api/v1/partner/* path prefix. Partners are identified by API key, and each key maps to a partner profile with specific permissions and rate limit overrides."
      },
      {
        "name": "Internal Ingress (Mesh/Private)",
        "responsibility": "Separate network path for internal service-to-service communication. No authentication required, but traffic is isolated at the network level (private subnet / service mesh). Enforces mutual TLS for transport security.",
        "boundaries": "NOT routed through the public API gateway. Accessible only from the internal VPC/network. Uses a lightweight internal gateway or service mesh sidecar for observability without auth overhead."
      },
      {
        "name": "Auth Service",
        "responsibility": "Centralized authentication and authorization. Issues and validates JWTs for mobile users. Manages API key lifecycle (creation, rotation, revocation) for partners. Provides a token introspection endpoint consumed by the gateway.",
        "boundaries": "Owns identity and credential storage. Does not make authorization decisions beyond token validity — resource-level authorization remains with backend services."
      },
      {
        "name": "Rate Limit Service",
        "responsibility": "Distributed rate limiting using a shared counter store (Redis). Exposes a check-and-decrement API consumed by the gateway on each request. Supports per-user, per-partner, and per-endpoint rate limit policies.",
        "boundaries": "Stateless compute layer backed by Redis. Policies are configured declaratively, not hardcoded. Failure mode: if Redis is unreachable, gateway fails open (allows traffic) with degraded metrics — not fail closed."
      },
      {
        "name": "Webhook Dispatcher",
        "responsibility": "Manages webhook subscriptions for B2B partners. Consumes domain events from backend services and delivers HTTP callbacks to partner-registered URLs with retry logic, exponential backoff, and delivery receipts.",
        "boundaries": "Decoupled from request path — operates asynchronously via event consumption. Owns webhook subscription storage and delivery state. Does not process inbound API requests."
      },
      {
        "name": "Backend Services (Existing)",
        "responsibility": "Existing logistics domain services (orders, tracking, inventory, etc.). With the gateway in place, these services shed all auth and rate limiting code and trust that requests arriving on the internal network are pre-authorized.",
        "boundaries": "Receive requests only from the gateway (external) or internal mesh (service-to-service). Must validate the X-Consumer-Type and X-Consumer-Id headers injected by the gateway for audit purposes."
      }
    ],
    "interfaces": [
      {
        "from": "Mobile App",
        "to": "API Gateway (Mobile Ingress)",
        "contract": "HTTPS with Bearer JWT in Authorization header. Gateway validates JWT signature and expiry, extracts user_id, injects X-Consumer-Type: mobile and X-Consumer-Id: {user_id} headers before forwarding.",
        "coupling_type": "loose — mobile app depends only on stable public API contract, not gateway internals"
      },
      {
        "from": "Partner Systems",
        "to": "API Gateway (Partner Ingress)",
        "contract": "HTTPS with API key in X-API-Key header. Gateway validates key against Auth Service, resolves partner_id and scopes, injects X-Consumer-Type: partner and X-Consumer-Id: {partner_id} headers.",
        "coupling_type": "loose — partners depend on published API spec and key provisioning process"
      },
      {
        "from": "API Gateway",
        "to": "Rate Limit Service",
        "contract": "Synchronous gRPC or HTTP call: POST /check with {consumer_type, consumer_id, endpoint}. Returns {allowed: bool, remaining: int, retry_after: int}. Gateway blocks request if allowed=false, returns 429.",
        "coupling_type": "operational coupling — gateway depends on rate limiter availability, mitigated by fail-open policy"
      },
      {
        "from": "API Gateway",
        "to": "Auth Service",
        "contract": "For JWTs: local validation using cached public keys (JWKS endpoint, refreshed every 5 min) — no per-request call. For API keys: synchronous lookup with local cache (TTL 60s) to avoid per-request latency.",
        "coupling_type": "loose — JWT validation is local; API key lookup is cached with graceful degradation"
      },
      {
        "from": "API Gateway",
        "to": "Backend Services",
        "contract": "HTTP/gRPC forwarding with injected headers: X-Consumer-Type, X-Consumer-Id, X-Request-Id, X-Rate-Limit-Remaining. Backend services trust these headers from the internal network.",
        "coupling_type": "loose — gateway routes by path prefix, backend services are independently deployable"
      },
      {
        "from": "Backend Services",
        "to": "Webhook Dispatcher",
        "contract": "Asynchronous domain events published to message broker (e.g., Kafka/SQS). Events include: order.created, shipment.updated, delivery.completed. Dispatcher subscribes and delivers to registered partner webhooks.",
        "coupling_type": "decoupled — async event-driven, no direct dependency"
      },
      {
        "from": "Internal Services",
        "to": "Backend Services (via mesh)",
        "contract": "Direct HTTP/gRPC over private network with mTLS. No gateway hop. Observability via service mesh sidecar (Envoy/Linkerd). Caller injects X-Consumer-Type: internal.",
        "coupling_type": "infrastructure coupling — depends on mesh/network configuration, not application-level gateway"
      }
    ],
    "data_flow": "External request → Load Balancer → API Gateway → [1] Auth check (JWT local validation or API key cache lookup) → [2] Rate limit check (Redis-backed counter) → [3] Route to backend service with enriched headers → Backend processes and responds → Gateway forwards response to caller. For webhooks: Backend emits domain event → Message broker → Webhook Dispatcher → HTTP POST to partner URL with HMAC signature for verification. Internal traffic bypasses the gateway entirely: Internal service → private network / service mesh → Backend service.",
    "patterns_used": [
      {
        "pattern": "API Gateway (Edge Gateway)",
        "rationale": "Centralizes cross-cutting concerns (auth, rate limiting, routing) that are currently scattered inconsistently across services. Single point of policy enforcement eliminates the root cause of inconsistent auth implementations."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Consumer-based routing with pipeline isolation",
        "rationale": "Three consumer types have fundamentally different auth mechanisms and rate limits. Separate ingress pipelines within a single gateway deployment avoid the operational overhead of three separate gateways while maintaining clean policy separation."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Network-level isolation for internal traffic",
        "rationale": "Internal services need zero auth overhead but must be unreachable from the public internet. Network isolation (private subnet + service mesh) is simpler and more secure than adding an 'internal' auth mode to the gateway."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Async webhook delivery via event consumption",
        "rationale": "Webhook delivery is inherently asynchronous and unreliable (partner endpoints may be down). Decoupling it from the request path via a message broker enables independent retry logic, backpressure handling, and delivery guarantees without affecting API latency."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Local JWT validation with JWKS caching",
        "rationale": "Avoids a synchronous call to the Auth Service on every mobile request. JWT signature validation is a local CPU operation using cached public keys, adding sub-millisecond latency instead of a network hop."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Fail-open rate limiting",
        "rationale": "If Redis is unreachable, the gateway allows traffic rather than rejecting all requests. Availability is prioritized over strict rate enforcement during infrastructure failures — a brief burst is preferable to a total outage."
      }
    ]
  },

  "domain_model": {
    "bounded_contexts": [
      {
        "name": "API Access Control",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["ConsumerProfile (root: consumer_id — holds auth credentials, rate limit tier, scopes)", "APIKey (entity within ConsumerProfile — key value, status, created_at, last_rotated)", "RateLimitPolicy (value object — requests_per_minute, burst_allowance, window_type)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Webhook Management",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["WebhookSubscription (root: subscription_id — partner_id, target_url, event_types, signing_secret, status)", "DeliveryAttempt (entity — timestamp, response_code, next_retry_at)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Logistics Core",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["Existing domain aggregates (orders, shipments, tracking, inventory) — unchanged by this design. Gateway architecture is orthogonal to domain model."]
      }
    ],
    "context_map": [
      {
        "upstream": "API Access Control",
        "downstream": "API Gateway",
        "relationship": "Open Host Service — Auth Service exposes JWKS and key-validation endpoints as a stable published interface consumed by the gateway."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Logistics Core",
        "downstream": "Webhook Management",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier — Core services publish domain events. Webhook Management subscribes and adapts them for partner delivery. Core does not know about webhooks."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "API Access Control",
        "downstream": "Webhook Management",
        "relationship": "Conformist — Webhook Management uses partner_id from API Access Control to associate subscriptions with partners. It conforms to the identity model."
      }
    ]
  },

  "trade_offs": [
    {
      "decision": "Single gateway deployment with logical pipeline separation (not three separate gateways)",
      "gains": "Lower operational overhead — one deployment to monitor, scale, and update. Shared infrastructure (load balancer, TLS termination, logging). Simpler DNS configuration.",
      "sacrifices": "A misconfiguration in one pipeline could theoretically affect others. Scaling is uniform rather than per-consumer-type. Blast radius is larger than fully isolated gateways.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Three separate gateway deployments (one per consumer type) — rejected due to 3x operational overhead for a team that currently has zero gateway experience", "BFF (Backend-for-Frontend) per consumer — rejected as premature; response shaping differences are minimal today"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Network-level isolation for internal traffic instead of routing through the gateway",
      "gains": "Zero latency overhead for internal calls. No single point of failure for internal communication. Simpler internal service development (no auth tokens to manage).",
      "sacrifices": "Two traffic paths to monitor instead of one. Internal services must be deployed in the correct network segment. Requires infrastructure-level enforcement (VPC rules, security groups).",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Route internal traffic through gateway with a 'skip-auth' flag — rejected as dangerous; a misconfigured flag exposes internal endpoints to the internet", "mTLS-only for all traffic including internal — considered viable but adds certificate management overhead for internal services that currently have none"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Fail-open rate limiting when Redis is unavailable",
      "gains": "System remains available during Redis outages. No cascading failure from rate limiter to all API consumers.",
      "sacrifices": "Brief periods of unenforced rate limits during Redis failures. Potential for abuse during outage windows.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Fail-closed (reject all requests when Redis is down) — rejected; availability is more important than strict rate enforcement for a logistics platform", "Local in-memory rate limiting as fallback — viable addition but adds complexity; recommend as Phase 2 enhancement"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "JWT for mobile, API keys for partners (not a unified auth mechanism)",
      "gains": "Each mechanism fits its consumer's workflow. JWTs enable stateless validation at the gateway. API keys are simple for partner integration and easy to rotate.",
      "sacrifices": "Two auth code paths to maintain. Gateway must handle both validation modes.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["OAuth2 for both — rejected; OAuth2 client credentials flow adds unnecessary complexity for partners who just want a static key", "API keys for both — rejected; JWTs provide better mobile session management with expiry and refresh token flows"]
    }
  ],

  "flexibility_points": [
    {
      "area": "Rate limit policies",
      "evolution_path": "Policies are declarative configuration, not code. Can add per-endpoint limits, burst allowances, tiered pricing, or dynamic rate adjustment without code changes. Redis-backed counters can be swapped for a managed rate limiting service."
    },
    {
      "area": "Gateway technology choice",
      "evolution_path": "Architecture is technology-agnostic. Can be implemented with Kong, AWS API Gateway, Envoy, NGINX, or a custom gateway. The logical pipeline separation maps to route groups in any gateway product."
    },
    {
      "area": "Adding new consumer types",
      "evolution_path": "New consumer types (e.g., admin dashboard, third-party marketplace) require only a new ingress pipeline configuration with appropriate auth and rate limit policies. No backend service changes needed."
    },
    {
      "area": "Webhook event types",
      "evolution_path": "New domain events can be added to webhook delivery by subscribing the Webhook Dispatcher to additional event topics. Partners opt-in to new event types through subscription configuration."
    }
  ],

  "rigidity_points": [
    {
      "area": "Network boundary between external and internal traffic",
      "reason": "This is a security invariant. Internal services MUST NOT be reachable from the public internet. This boundary should be enforced at the infrastructure level (VPC, security groups) and never relaxed for convenience."
    },
    {
      "area": "Gateway owns all external auth — backend services must NOT independently authenticate external requests",
      "reason": "The entire point of this architecture is centralizing auth. If any backend service starts validating JWTs or API keys independently, we're back to the current inconsistency problem. This must be an enforced team convention."
    },
    {
      "area": "Consumer identity headers (X-Consumer-Type, X-Consumer-Id) are injected only by the gateway",
      "reason": "Backend services trust these headers because they come from the internal network. If external callers could forge them, the auth model collapses. The gateway must strip any incoming X-Consumer-* headers from external requests."
    }
  ],

  "risks": [
    {
      "risk": "Gateway becomes a single point of failure for all external API traffic",
      "severity": "critical",
      "mitigation": "Deploy gateway as a stateless, horizontally-scaled cluster behind a load balancer with health checks. Target 3+ instances across availability zones. Implement circuit breakers for downstream service failures so the gateway itself stays responsive (returns 503) rather than hanging."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Migration from per-service auth to centralized gateway auth causes outages during cutover",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Phase the migration: (1) Deploy gateway in shadow mode — routes traffic but does not enforce auth. (2) Enable auth enforcement per-route incrementally. (3) Remove per-service auth only after gateway auth is verified per-route. Run both in parallel during transition with monitoring for auth mismatches."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Redis failure disables rate limiting, allowing traffic spikes to overwhelm backend services",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Fail-open policy accepts this risk for availability. Mitigate by: (1) Redis cluster with replicas for HA. (2) Local in-memory approximate rate limiter as fallback (Phase 2). (3) Backend services should have their own circuit breakers and load shedding as a defense-in-depth measure."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Webhook delivery to unreliable partner endpoints causes unbounded queue growth",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Implement a dead-letter queue after N failed delivery attempts (recommend 5 attempts with exponential backoff over 24 hours). Provide partners with a webhook delivery dashboard showing failures. Auto-disable subscriptions after prolonged failure (7 days) with notification to partner."
    },
    {
      "risk": "API key leakage for B2B partners",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Store API keys hashed (bcrypt/argon2), not plaintext. Enforce key rotation policy (90-day max lifetime). Support multiple active keys per partner to enable zero-downtime rotation. Implement key usage anomaly detection (sudden IP change, usage spike)."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Latency added by gateway hop degrades mobile app experience",
      "severity": "low",
      "mitigation": "JWT validation is local (sub-millisecond). Rate limit check is a single Redis round-trip (~1-2ms). Total gateway overhead should be <5ms. Monitor P99 gateway latency and set alerts at 20ms. If latency grows, profile and optimize before considering bypass."
    }
  ],

  "implementation_guidance": {
    "recommended_approach": "Implement in three phases. Phase 1 (Week 1-2): Deploy the gateway in pass-through mode with logging only. Set up the Auth Service with JWKS endpoint for mobile JWTs and API key storage for partners. Phase 2 (Week 3-4): Enable auth enforcement route-by-route, starting with the least critical endpoints. Deploy Redis-backed rate limiting. Remove auth code from backend services as each route is verified. Phase 3 (Week 5-6): Build Webhook Dispatcher, integrate with domain events, and onboard first partner webhook subscriber. For technology selection: if already on AWS, start with AWS API Gateway + Lambda authorizers (lowest operational lift). If on Kubernetes, use Kong or Envoy-based gateway (more flexible). Avoid building a custom gateway from scratch.",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "infrastructure/api-gateway/ — gateway configuration (routes, plugins, policies)",
      "services/auth-service/ — new service: JWT issuance, JWKS endpoint, API key management",
      "services/rate-limiter/ — rate limit check service backed by Redis",
      "services/webhook-dispatcher/ — new service: subscription management, event consumption, HTTP delivery",
      "infrastructure/networking/ — VPC/security group rules enforcing internal traffic isolation",
      "services/*/middleware/auth.* — REMOVE per-service auth middleware after gateway cutover (per-route, phased)",
      "docs/adr/001-api-gateway-architecture.md — Architecture Decision Record documenting this design"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Use declarative gateway configuration (YAML/JSON route definitions, not imperative code). Rate limit policies should be configurable per consumer-type and per-endpoint without redeployment. Webhook delivery should use an outbox pattern or reliable event consumption from the message broker — never fire-and-forget HTTP calls from backend services. All gateway components must emit structured logs with X-Request-Id correlation for distributed tracing.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "Do NOT put business logic in the gateway — it should only handle cross-cutting concerns. The moment you add request transformation or data aggregation, you've created a distributed monolith.",
      "Do NOT skip the shadow/parallel-run phase during migration. Cutting over auth in a big bang guarantees an outage.",
      "Do NOT use a shared Redis instance for rate limiting and application caching. Rate limiting needs predictable latency; a cache eviction storm should not affect rate limit accuracy.",
      "Do NOT allow backend services to remain 'dual-auth' (checking both gateway headers AND their own auth) long-term. This creates confusion about which layer is authoritative. Set a deadline to remove per-service auth.",
      "Do NOT expose internal service endpoints through the gateway 'for convenience'. The internal/external boundary is a security invariant.",
      "Do NOT hardcode partner rate limits. Use a partner profile/tier system so limits can be adjusted without gateway redeployment."
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 85,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "Gateway pattern is the correct solution for centralizing auth and rate limiting — this is a textbook use case",
      "Network-level isolation for internal traffic is the right approach given the 'no auth needed' requirement",
      "Phased migration strategy is essential to avoid outages",
      "JWT for mobile + API keys for partners is the right auth split for these consumer types"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Specific gateway technology choice depends on existing infrastructure (cloud provider, container orchestration) which was not specified",
      "Webhook delivery guarantees depend on message broker choice and partner SLA requirements not yet defined",
      "Whether fail-open rate limiting is acceptable depends on the severity of abuse risk, which varies by endpoint"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "Backend services are deployed in a private network segment that can be isolated from public internet traffic",
      "A message broker (Kafka, SQS, or similar) is available or can be introduced for webhook event delivery",
      "Redis or equivalent can be provisioned for distributed rate limiting",
      "The team has operational capacity to manage a gateway deployment (monitoring, scaling, incident response)",
      "Mobile app already uses some form of user authentication (login flow exists) that can be adapted to issue JWTs"
    ]
  }
}

